name: John F. Kennedy
description:
John Fitzgerald Kennedy (May 29, 1917 – November 22, 1963), known by his nicknames "Jack" or the initials JFK, was the 35th President of the United States who served from January 1961 until his assassination in November 1963.

After serving in the military as commander of the PT-109 and PT-59 Motor Torpedo Ships during World War II in the South Pacific, Kennedy was the Democratic Party's 11th congressional district representative in the United States House of Representatives from 1947 to 1953. After that, he served in the United States Senate from 1953 to 1960. Kennedy defeated Vice President and Republican candidate Richard Nixon in the 1960 US presidential election. At the age of 43, he became the youngest president ever to serve,[2][a] youngest president. second (after Theodore Roosevelt), and the first president born in the 20th century.[3] To this day, Kennedy, a Catholic, is the only non-Protestant president and the only Pulitzer Prize-winning president.
